Rollout and Rollback
====================
--- 
 - Rollout and Rollback in Kubernetes are key features of Deployments that help manage application updates smoothly.

 Rollout => update packages on lastet version.
 Rollback => rollback on previous version.


Rollout (Deployment Updates)
🔹 Rollout is the process of deploying a new version of an application in a controlled manner.
🔹 Kubernetes ensures zero downtime using a rolling update strategy (default).


# kubectl create deployment dep1 --image=docker.io/nginx:1.16 --replicas=10
# kubectl rollout status deployment my-app
# kubectl rollout history deployment my-app


---
Rollback (Reverting to a Previous Version)
🔹 Rollback allows you to revert to a previous Deployment version if a new rollout fails.
🔹 Kubernetes keeps a history of old rollouts to allow quick recovery.

# kubectl rollout undo deployment my-app
# kubectl rollout undo deployment my-app --to-revision=2



---
Q) Rollout Strategy: Recreate vs RollingUpdate

 - Kubernetes supports two rollout strategies:

 Strategy	               | Description	                                          | Pros	         | Cons
 Recreate	               | Deletes all old pods before creating new ones	        | Simple	       | Causes downtime
 RollingUpdate (default)	| Replaces old pods gradually	Zero downtime	Takes longer| Zero downtime | Takes longer


---
Best Practices for Rollouts & Rollbacks
✅ Always test updates in a staging environment before rolling out.
✅ Monitor rollout status (kubectl rollout status) to detect failures early.
✅ Use rollback (kubectl rollout undo) to quickly revert bad deployments.
✅ Set health checks (readiness & liveness probes) to prevent broken rollouts.


